args:
The faerie Meene is Ilia's surrogate mother,
her love going beyond the difference in race.
This love helps Zethia realize that though this
world is a different history than her own, there
are still things in it to be protected. Meanwhile,
Ilia finally susses out the truth about Zethia.

A thousand years ago, with the development of
alchemy, humanity reached great heights in its
prosperity, its iron cities sprawling across the
earth and into the sky.
But while humans enjoyed peace and\npleasures alike, this brought ruin to nature\nand sickened its mana.

This disruption of nature and mana alike ate
away at the dragons and threatened to rob
them of their very lives, and they eventually
launched a war against the humans.

The struggle was terribly fierce, and was said
to have continued for so long that some
foresaw no end to the bloodshed. Eventually,
the short-lived humans grew impatient with the
situation and began a new and reckless plan:
To achieve victory over the dragons, they built\na key to open a gate to another world, and from\nit summoned forth a calamity.
But this calamity was not an ally; neither\nhuman nor dragon, it brought ruin to all,\nand the world was soon plunged into despair.
This calamity, which humans called forth from\nthe ends of existence, eventually became\nknown as the Other.

One dragon in particular was gravely concerned
over the collapse of order the Other brought
about: the Holywyrm Elysium, greatest among
dragons and the ruler of light.

Elysium chose a single human of noble spirit
and formed a pact with her. This human was
the first Auspex, Ilia, who came to be revered
in later years as the Goddess.

Ilia traveled with Elysium and proselytized
far and wide, telling all that reclaiming the
bonds held between people and dragons in
ages past would grant the power needed to
stand against the Other.

People found hope in their appearances,
and eventually discarded their enmity with
the dragons and fought together at their side.
After a long and difficult struggle, the Other
was finally sealed away.
In the years since, humanity abandoned the\nexcesses of civilization and chose to live a\nsimpler life together with dragons.
This is the story of the First War of Binding,\nwhich begat the beginning of Ilian history.
...That is the history I know—but it\nappears the past I find myself in now\nis wholly different.
In exchange for offering mana for Ilia to\nuse in her research, she has allowed me\nto stay in her home.
It has been several days since I first came\nto this era, and I have been unable to\ndecide what course I ought to take.

Woof! That's a toughie. Honestly, you'll
find as many opinions as there are people
in the world, so there really isn't one
that's THE right answer.
Love is something without an answer?
Sorta, yeah—which is why you have to find\nthe answer that works for you. But I have\ntotal faith you will someday!
(To see the two of them interact so...\nThis time period truly is completely\nunlike the history I know.)
(If my meeting with Ilia changed history,\nthen I must do all that I can to put things\nback to rights.)
(If I do not, it will have an impact on\nthe future, perhaps even leading to my\nsiblings and I not being born! And yet...)
Someone has their thinking face on.
Well, Ilia and Mordecai certainly seem\nto have become fast friends.
You were against Mordecai staying here,\nweren't you?
I was. Dragons and faeries and the like\ndislike beings from other worlds.
Humans and dragons are in conflict right\nnow, and I am wary of anything that could\ncause additional disturbance.

Further, there are many unknowns when
it comes to otherworldly beings.
If this thing brought harm to my Ilia, I...
Well, I just don't know what I would do.
You clearly love her very much.
I do. Her birth mother entrusted her to me\nwhen she was a baby, and I raised her as\nmy own from that day forth.
I changed when I met Ilia; she is more\nprecious to me than anything, which often\nleads to my being overprotective.
But while I am worried about this whole\nMordecai situation, a small part of me\nis also pleased that he is here.
Ilia does not much care for people,\nand until recently has shunned relations\nwith anyone other than myself.
Yet Mordecai and you both seem to have\ngood relationships with her.
It makes me think that if Mordecai were to\nremain here, Ilia would be able to get by\nwithout being lonely if I were gone.
We faeries have a period of adolescence\nin which our bodies grow large.
Only then are we are allowed to leave our\nkingdom and learn of the outside world.
But once our bodies return to their original\nsize, we return home to our land and can\nnever again leave it.
Yes. When that day comes—and it could\nbe any time—I will be parted from Ilia.
But so long as I know Ilia is happy,\nI will be content.
(In order for this world to progress\naccording to the history I know,\nthe Other must be summoned into it.)
(Yet that would mean ruination for a world\nwhere I now care for the people in it.)
(Is it truly right to summon forth the Other\nand bring about destruction here?)
(What ought I believe in?\nWhat ought I protect?)
O Goddess Ilia, please guide me...
I want to ask you something—I'm the sort\nwho can't sit still once something grabs\nmy attention, you know?
So sorry for getting right to the point,\nbut you're not from this world, are you?
Yeah, see, I've done a lot of research\ninto other worlds to help me figure out\nhow otherworld gates work.

And I know that that day I opened the gate,
there was another location—separate from
my lab—that experienced an interaction
with another world.

And then along comes this strange lady
who doesn't know the first thing about
alchemy or anything else that even the
most basic child of this era would know.

You're distant, you're secretive, and you
basically change the subject whenever
your past comes up. I mean, this isn't
alchemy—you're clearly not from here.
Anyway, I came up with a hypothesis:\nYou came here from some other world,\nentered the woods, and ran into me.

And you stopped me from opening the gate
because you're from the future and you
know something about what would have
happened if I did.
Assuming for a moment you are correct,\nwhat would you do with me?
Do? Oh, nothing! I just wanted to check my\nmath on this theory and see if I was right.
You wouldn't wish to ask me more\nquestions about the future or...anything?
Look, you're my friend and I trust you—\nand besides, it's not like I've spilled the\nbeans about all of MY secrets, either.
This is sorta my first time doing the whole\n＂friends＂ thing, and I'm not really sure\nwhat's right and what's not. ...Is that bad?
If you are happy with this arrangement,\nthen I am as well.
For sure. Anyway, that's all.\nCome back home before it gets cold, okay?
...I'd like to become closer friends with\nyou. I really mean it.
(She is completely unlike the Goddess Ilia\nthat I pictured in my mind—and yet, I am\nabsolutely certain that she is.)
Pray guide me, Goddess—and this world.
